":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Burton Constable, Yorkshire, England":"Burton Constable, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"–":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1264–Female":"1264–Deceased","1284–1335":"1284–1335","–1316":"–1316","–Female":"Deceased","1316":"1316","1315":"1315","before 1302":"before 1302","1335":"1335","1264":"1264","1284":"1284","1382":"1382","before 1316":"before 1316","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","Burton Constable, Yorkshire, England":"Burton Constable, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richmond","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["habitational name from Richmond (North Yorkshire). The placename was probably transferred after the Norman Conquest from any of numerous places in France named with Old French <i>riche</i> ‘mighty, strong’ + <i>munt</i>, <i>mont</i> ‘mountain, hill’. Richmond in southwest London received this name only in the reign of Henry VII, in honor of the king, who had been Earl of Richmond until he came to the throne, and is unlikely to be the source of this surname.","occasionally a variant of   Richman  , with excrescent <i>-d</i>. The two names were probably often confused.","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Richman","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Richeman</i>, either from an unrecorded Old English <i>Rīcmann</i>, or from a pet form of <i>Richard</i> + the hypocoristic suffix <i>-man</i>. The name was sometimes interchangeable with   Rickman  , especially in recent times.","English: occasionally perhaps a nickname from Middle English <i>riche</i> ‘rich, powerful’ + <i>-man</i>. Compare   Rich  .","English: perhaps a variant of   Richmond  , or vice versa."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":7,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":32,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":45,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":99,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"John Richmond was born in Burton Constable, Yorkshire, England as the son of Thomas Richmond and Mrs. Thomas Richmond. He married Van Veurne before 1302, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"–":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1264–Female":"1264–Surnud","1284–1335":"1284–1335","–1316":"–1316","–Female":"Surnud","1316":"13